I fixed it by pasting the vendordeps of an older project that already has most of the libraries imported into this new one. But whenever I want to import anything else that wasn’t imported in the older project I get the same error.

I have also experienced an issue similar before. It seems to be caused by something on the back-end (i.e. beyond my expertise) that is subverted by merely pasting in the vendor depositories into the correct location.

I remember trying several gradle commands such as gradle clean build --refresh-dependencies, but this won’t work.

Rather, you should (although annoying) go back through and add in each vendordep the manual (and correct) way using the WPILib VSCode plugin, which won’t skip the necessary procedures for vendordeps.

Just follow the steps found here.

  1. Delete the existing .json files
  2. Use ctrl + shift + p to open the command pallete
  3. Type Manage Vendor Deps, and select it
  4. Select install new vendordeps (online)
  5. Paste in the URL to the vendordeps, which can be found at the link above.
